 So about a year ago, almost to this very day, for the first time in my life,

16
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 I heard what I could only describe to you as the audible voice of God.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,000
 I was walking through the transit terminal of Doha International Airport.

18
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 I don't know if you've ever been to Doha International Airport.

19
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 It's one of the biggest airports in the world.

20
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,000
 The transit lounge and the transit hall there is massive.

21
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 And there are thousands of people that congregate into that place every day

22
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 that are passing through Doha on their way to anywhere in the world that you could imagine.

23
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 And I was there with an 11-hour layover.

24
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 The Vine had booked my flight to Jordan the cheapest way possible, in the name of Jesus.

25
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 I had an 11-hour layover in Jordan. Praise God.

26
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 And as I'm at the beginning of my 11-hour layover,

27
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:53,000
 I'm walking through one of the busiest parts of Doha International Airport.

28
00:01:53,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 And as I'm walking down this corridor where thousands of other people are,

29
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:04,000
 a Middle Eastern man walks right past me, almost brushes my shoulder.

30
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 We were pretty hemmed in. And almost brushes my shoulder and walks past me.

31
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:14,000
 And as he does, I hear the audible voice of God, "Follow him.

32
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 Follow him."

33
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:22,000
 It's hard to describe it to you, but it sounded like Morgan Freeman.

34
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 No, it didn't. It didn't sound like that.

35
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 I don't know really how it sounded, but it was the first time in my life

36
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 where I almost like, I was like, something like spoke to me,

37
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 or it was like this audible voice. And because it was so real,

38
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:38,000
 I immediately found myself following after the guy.

39
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:43,000
 And I literally like turned around and started following after him.

40
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 Not really knowing why I was following after him,

41
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 but I knew that I had been commanded to change my direction and follow him.

42
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 So I started walking about 10 feet behind him.

43
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
 And after about like maybe 20 yards or so, I was like feeling really weird about it.

44
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 Like, what am I doing following this guy? Like, who is he?

45
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:05,000
 I have no idea who he is. I have no idea why God wants me to follow him,

46
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 but I'm following him. And then I'm thinking like,

47
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 does he know that I'm following him? Because that would be weird.

48
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 Right? Like this is the Middle East. Maybe I'm about to get arrested.

49
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 Like what happens when you follow random people?

50
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 So I'm like following him and he kind of walks through this part of the airport

51
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,000
 and then he goes into the side. Now at the side of the transit hall in Doha,

52
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
 they have all these rooms and these rooms have like little lounge chairs in them

53
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 where people can go and sleep for a few hours.

54
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 And he walks into one of these rooms.

55
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
 There's probably about 30 or 40 of the chairs in the room

56
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 and he sits down on this chair. And I find myself walking into the room

57
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 and then very nonchalantly sort of, you're going to be him,

58
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 sort of sitting down right next to him like this, you know,

59
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 like kind of going like, why am I here? Right?

60
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 As I sit down, he leans forward and he starts to just weep.

61
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 He starts to sob his eyes out.

62
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 Now I've spent enough time in the Middle East to understand the culture there

63
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 and that's unusual in that Middle Eastern culture.

64
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 To be honest, it's unusual in the majority of cultures.

65
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 But particularly in that culture where men, a public display of emotion like that

66
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
 is not necessarily looked upon as a good thing.

67
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 But he just leans forward, head in his hand, just weeping

68
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 and immediately pasta mode of Andrew takes over, right?

69
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 And I've been in this scenario a number of times.

70
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
 This was a bit of a weird one, I admit, like following this guy.

71
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 But I've been in this scenario a number of times.

72
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 So I just kind of like, again, you're him and I'm me, right?

73
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 So you're sobbing. Go on, sob. No, no, sit, sit, sit.

74
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 Head in hand, cry, cry. Yeah, okay, good.

75
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 So I'm there.

76
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:58,000
 You're never going to sit in the front row ever again, never.

77
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 Neither is anybody else. All right.

78
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 So you're crying.

79
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 So I lean forward and I go like this.

80
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 I'm like, "Hey, I'm so sorry. Is there anything I can do to help?"

81
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 Thank you.

82
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 So he turns to me and he points at his mouth like this,

83
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 basically saying, "I don't speak English."

84
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 So I kind of like smile and I point to my mouth,

85
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
 basically saying, "I don't really speak English."

86
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 No, like, "I don't speak Arabic," is what I was trying to say to him.

87
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 "I don't really speak Arabic." And he kind of nodded.

88
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 And he looked kind of embarrassed, as you can imagine, right?

89
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 But I was like, "I can't communicate to this man,

90
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 but I can be present with him."

91
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 So I kind of just sat there and I leaned towards him again

92
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 and I kind of put my hands like this in my lap,

93
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 like very pastoral, right?

94
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 And I kind of like just smiled at him,

95
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 you know, like trying to communicate, "I'm here," right?

96
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 Well, he kind of wipes his eyes,

97
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 and I think he's feeling a little embarrassed,

98
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 so he gets out his mobile phone and he flips through it

99
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 and he shows me what I assume was a picture of his family,

100
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 beautiful family, massive large family, beautiful family.

101
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 And so I like got my phone out, you know,

102
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 and scrolled and showed a picture of my dog.

103
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,000
 No, I showed my wife and daughter, don't worry.

104
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 I showed a picture of my family as well,

105
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 and he had this face, like it was classic.

106
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 He had this face like, "Wow, that's your family?

107
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 Like, you did well."

108
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 He was like, "You managed that? Good job," right?

109
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 So he was kind of looking at me like that,

110
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 and I was like smiling, "Family," you know.

111
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 And then he kind of like put his phone away,

112
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 and then he stood up and he just walked away.

113
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 And that was it.

114
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 That was the whole interaction.

115
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 I have no idea to this day who that man was.

116
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 I have no idea what was going on in his life,

117
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
 but I do know this.

118
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 I do know that God loved that man so much,

119
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 that God cared for that man so much

120
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 that he would disrupt my just normal day,

121
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 11-hour layover in Doha, trying to be just a tourist,

122
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 and change me into that pastor

123
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 who could then follow him in a moment

124
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 where his emotions were obviously just sort of built up inside of him,

125
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 and those emotions just suddenly come out,

126
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 and I can sit there with him,

127
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 and I realized what was taking place.

128
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 Even though I could not communicate to him,

129
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 here's what was happening.

130
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 I was a non-anxious presence amid the chaos of this man's world.

131
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 Just in that moment of time,

132
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:37,000
 a non-anxious presence in his life.

133
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:41,000
 You need to know that God desires to take you

134
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 in and out of places of rest

135
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 so that you would then become a place of rest for others.

136
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 That's what this series is all about.

137
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:56,000
 It's what actually Psalm 23 is all about.

138
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,000
 As I said last week, it's not just a psalm

139
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 to make us feel good about ourselves,

140
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,000
 to chill out with God,

141
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 a psalm for us to feel like we can relax.

142
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 The psalm is actually to create in us a place of rest,

143
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 a place of life, a place of restoration with God

144
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 so that we can then be that to others in this world

145
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 who are freaked out, who can't handle it,

146
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:20,000
 and we are there with them in the midst of their chaos,

147
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 communicating something of the peace,

148
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 the shalom, the restoration that God has given us.

149
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 And God's heart for you is to lead you

150
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 in and out of those places of rest

151
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
 so you would be the embodied rest of God for others.

152
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 Are you with me, church?

153
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 It's this idea of God leading his people into rest

154
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 that David shifts to after his opening verse.

155
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 His opening verse of Psalm 23, "The Lord is my shepherd.

156
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 I shall not be in want."

157
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 And then he immediately starts talking about leadership,

158
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 about how a shepherd leads his people.

159
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 Let me read this to you in verses two and three.

160
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 "He makes me lie down in green pastures.

161
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 He leads me beside quiet waters.

162
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 He restores my soul.

163
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 He guides me in paths of righteousness

164
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 or right paths for his name's sake."

165
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 Just a short couple of verses, but this is David at his best.

166
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:19,000
 This is David writing a psalm.

167
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 Remember, psalms were poems.

168
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 He's writing a poem like a song.

169
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 And in his writing, he's trying to express

170
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:28,000
 some beautiful imagery to help us to understand

171
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 the rest and the peace that God provides,

172
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 not only for ourselves, but for all of his creation.

173
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:37,000
 And he's also trying to teach some deep theological truths

174
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 through this poetic imagery.

175
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 Now, if you are to read this in the Hebrew,

176
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 you actually get a much better sense of the poetic form

177
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 and structure that David's trying to create.

178
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 In fact, his whole argument in these two verses

179
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 is based around a specific poetic structure.

180
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 In the Hebrew, he basically goes, "Here's an action of God.

181
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 Here's a place that God takes us to, and here's the result."

182
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,000
 Let me actually show you this structure here.

183
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 This is the structure of Psalm 23, verses two and three.

184
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 Here's a few things I want you to see.

185
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 First of all, I want you to see the right-hand column,

186
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 the result.

187
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 This is what God is doing in you.

188
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 This is what David is trying to communicate to his people

189
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,000
 as he writes this, that God's desire is to bring you

190
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:24,000
 into a place of rest, a place of peace,

191
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 the shalom of God in you, that would bring restoration,

192
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 change and transform you so that you're not like you were before,

193
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 but you're now a new person, a new human being

194
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 with a level of deep rest and peace that you've never had before.

195
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 Why? So that God has glory on the earth,

196
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,000
 so that God gets glory.

197
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 He doesn't want you just to be at rest so that you can enjoy yourself.

198
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 This is not about being on Bali with a pina colada.

199
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 This is about you becoming the person Christ wants you to be

200
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 in the craziness of the world around you.

201
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 This is you being a restful presence for God's glory.

202
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 David's saying that's what God wants.

203
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 That's what he's constantly trying to bring into our lives.

204
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 How does he do it?

205
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 First of all, he has to bring us into certain experiences

206
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 that will create in us the result of the rest and peace.

207
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 Are you following this?

208
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 So there are places that he takes us to.

209
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 Now, David metaphorically, poetically describes these places

210
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 as green pastures, quiet waters, right paths.

211
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 And what he's saying is if you do not go through these places,

212
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 you will not experience the rest that God wants you to have.

213
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 Are you following the argument?

214
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 So in order to go into those places, he then says at the start,

215
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 there is an action.

216
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:45,000
 There's something God does to bring us into those places

217
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 to create the rest.

218
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 He makes us, leads us, and guides us to certain experiences

219
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 so those experiences transform us and create the result,

220
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:59,000
 the fruit of rest and peace that is seen publicly

221
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 so God gets the glory.

222
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 Are you following this?

223
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 This is David's heart for this part of the psalm.

224
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:09,000
 If I was to say it simply, this is what David's saying.

225
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:16,000
 If you truly want to experience and know his rest,

226
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 then you need to allow yourself to experience the one thing

227
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 that God desires to do the most in you, and that is lead you.

228
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 Lead you.

229
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:31,000
 If you truly want to know rest, you have to be willing to allow God

230
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:37,000
 to lead you, lead you into places that will do its work in you

231
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 to create that rest.

232
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 And this is a challenge because David's saying,

233
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:47,000
 "There's a prerogative here, and the prerogative is God's leadership

234
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 of your life."

235
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:51,000
 You remember last week when we looked at the opening of the psalm

236
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 where we said, "The Lord is my shepherd.

237
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 I shall not be in want," and we said we can flip that around

238
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 and say it in reverse.

239
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 In other words, we can say, "I have wants.

240
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 Therefore, the Lord is not quite my shepherd."

241
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:04,000
 Well, in the same way, you can flip this around as well.

